I also have a question about design approach @joelriou . In [https://github.com/Paul-Lez/Stacks-project](https://github.com/Paul-Lez/Stacks-project), we have a notion of `BasedCategory` defined as follows:
```
/-- A based category over `ùíÆ` is a category `ùí≥` together with a functor `p : ùí≥ ‚•§ ùíÆ` -/
structure BasedCategory (ùíÆ : Type u‚ÇÅ) [Category.{v‚ÇÅ} ùíÆ] where
  (cat : Type u‚ÇÇ)
  [isCat : Category.{v‚ÇÇ} cat]
  (p : cat ‚•§ ùíÆ)
```
We developed this as a preliminary step to dealing with functors between different fibered categories, and we showed that `BasedCategory ùíÆ` forms a strict bicategory. Now, do you think it could be good to rewrite the code defining `IsFibered` and `IsCartesian` to use `ùí≥ : BasedCategory ùíÆ` as a parameter instead of `p : ùí≥ ‚•§ ùíÆ`? Or is it unecessary to lock `p` inside `ùí≥ : BasedCategory ùíÆ`, since we don't talk about functors between (pre-)fibered categories in this PR anyways?

Here is an update on this PR. I have split it into 4 smaller PRs. This one now only concerns the definition of a fibered category, defined as in SGA, and also an alternate constructor for using the definition as in e.g. Stacks project.

This is not the definition of a fibered category, this is a *pre*fibered category. Fibered category are prefibered category where the composition of two cartesian morphisms is cartesian, see SGA 1 VI 6.1.

I am using a different notion of `IsCartesian` to SGA, the fact that composition of two cartesian arrows is cartesian follows and is lemma `IsCartesian.comp`. It seems that in SGA they only require the universal property to be satisfied for `R'=R` (with notation as in the code). Most books on stacks that I have read define them the way we did here, for example Olsson's book. Do you think it's better to define cartesian arrows as in SGA (and then adjust the definition of `IsFibered`)?

The notion of prefibered category appears in certain results in the homotopy theory of categories (how certain properties of functors become homotopy equivalences, fibrations, etc, after passing to the nerve), typically Quillen's higher algebraic K-theory. Then, I feel it would be worth defining the notion of prefibered category also. (What you call "cartesian", it is what is named "strongly cartesian" at https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/02XJ ?) For fibered categories, different constructors could be introduced depending on whether we check the expected properties using cartesian or strongly cartesian morphisms.
Okay, then I will work to do everything in this generality!
I have added this now (although there is still some cleaning up & documentation to write). I think I will split this PR into two: `Cartesian` and `Fibered` once it is ready again.
